**Issue:**

Use FillBytes to encode your hand(s) and get the error:
`OverflowException: Value was either too large or too small for an Int16.`

from line:
`LeapMotion/Core/Scripts/Encoding/VectorHand.cs:239)`

**Reproduce:**

- Start a new scene, remove the main camera, drag Leap Rig prefab into scene.
- Add the following script to the Leap Rig Game Object

```
using Leap;
using Leap.Unity;
using Leap.Unity.Encoding;
using UnityEngine;

public class LeapTestVector : MonoBehaviour
{
    LeapXRServiceProvider leap;
    VectorHand vectorHand = new VectorHand();

    void Start()
    {
        leap = GetComponentInChildren<LeapXRServiceProvider>();
        leap.OnUpdateFrame += OnUpdateFrame;
    }

    private void OnUpdateFrame(Frame obj)
    {
        byte[] leftHandBytes = null;
        byte[] rightHandBytes = null;
        foreach (Hand hand in obj.Hands)
        {
            vectorHand.Encode(hand);
            if (hand.IsLeft)
            {
                leftHandBytes = new byte[86];
                vectorHand.FillBytes(leftHandBytes);
            }
            else
            {
                rightHandBytes = new byte[86];
                vectorHand.FillBytes(rightHandBytes);
            }
        }

    }
}
```
- Move the Leap Rig's X or Z Position to 8 or -8.
- See errors.

Am I using VectorHand wrong? Above is just a snippet of the code I'm using, I know I can tidy it up, I'm sending the byte array over the network to show hands on other clients...
